          "title": "Scene 1",
          "order": 0,
          "content": "<p>The last guest left at eleven. Vivian watched the taillights shrink down the gravel drive from the master suite window, then turned. Her heels clicked marble. The Atlantic did what it always did outside — threw itself at the cliffs, pulled back, threw itself again.</p><p>Twelve-foot ceilings. A bed for six. White roses in every corner, scent thick enough to choke on. Someone had designed this room to look like the inside of a love story.</p><p>The woman in the glass wore Valentino. Custom. He&#39;d sent it to her apartment three weeks ago — *I wanted to see you in white* — and she&#39;d almost laughed. Almost. Elegant. Composed. Untouchable. The kind of woman who marries a billionaire for love, not because a handler with a dead man&#39;s name told her to.</p><p>She touched her left ear. Empty. The earpiece was in her clutch — she&#39;d pulled it during the reception, told MERIDIAN the unit was defective, tucked it into the lining next to her lipstick and the thing she hoped she wouldn&#39;t need. The lamp fixture mic was still live. He&#39;d hear through that. He just wouldn&#39;t hear her.</p><p>The zipper ran down her back like a secret being told. She stepped out of the dress, hung it in the closet. Valentino. She handled it like it mattered.</p><p>In the bathroom — bigger than her first apartment, all of them in the Bronx — she washed the makeup off. Contour. Nude lipstick. False lashes that made her eyes soft. Underneath: the woman the Bureau spent six years building.</p><p>She looked at herself.</p><p>*You&#39;ve done worse. Prague. The arms dealer who slept with a Sig Sauer under his pillow and you lifted his phone while he snored. Sinaloa. Three months in a cartel compound playing girlfriend to a man who laundered money the way other people breathe.*</p><p>True. All of it. She&#39;d done things that would make the woman in that dress scream.</p><p>But this was marriage. A year, maybe two, playing house with a man the Bureau said moved eight hundred women across borders in ten years. The file put the number at eight hundred. Files lied — she knew that better than anyone — but eight hundred was a hard number to fake.</p><p>She dried her face. The robe on the bed was pale blue, his initials on the pocket. It smelled like cedar and something underneath the cedar. She hated that she noticed.</p><p>The door opened.</p><p>She didn&#39;t turn. Watched him in the mirror instead. Alexander Voss removing his cufflinks. Setting them on the dresser — not dropping, *setting* — with the kind of precision that suggested he&#39;d rehearsed it. Still in the tuxedo. Still perfect. Still the man from the photographs, except photographs didn&#39;t capture how he moved. Like every step was calculated before his foot hit the floor.</p><p>&quot;You left before I could dance with you.&quot;</p><p>&quot;I was tired.&quot; She turned. Leaned against the counter. Let the robe slip off one shoulder — not too much. &quot;Long day.&quot;</p>",
