          "id": "sc-01-02",
          "title": "Scene 2",
          "order": 1,
          "content": "<p>&quot;It was.&quot; He loosened his tie. Didn&#39;t remove it. Just loosened it. His eyes moved over her — not desire, not appreciation. Something colder. Taking inventory. &quot;You were beautiful tonight.&quot;</p><p>&quot;Thank you.&quot;</p><p>&quot;Observation. Not a compliment.&quot;</p><p>Her stomach dropped. Just a fraction. Just enough.</p><p>He crossed the room. Stopped three feet away. Close enough that the cedar reached her, and under it, something older. Smoke after a fire&#39;s gone out.</p><p>&quot;I know what you&#39;re thinking.&quot;</p><p>&quot;What am I thinking?&quot;</p><p>&quot;How to do this. How to play the blushing bride.&quot; He tilted his head. &quot;You&#39;re thinking about your handler. Whether he&#39;s listening.&quot;</p><p>*Your handler.* Not *a* handler. *Your* handler.</p><p>She stopped breathing. Didn&#39;t mean to. Just forgot how.</p><p>Six years of training kept her face still. Six years of lying to killers, traffickers, men who would put a bullet in her skull. Still.</p><p>&quot;I don&#39;t know what you&#39;re talking about.&quot;</p><p>&quot;Yes, you do.&quot; One step closer. Two feet now. &quot;But that&#39;s alright. I&#39;m not going to make this difficult.&quot;</p><p>He reached out. Touched her face. His fingers were warm and so gentle it made her angry — angry at him, angrier at herself for the lean into his touch she didn&#39;t authorize.</p><p>&quot;You&#39;re my wife now,&quot; he said. &quot;And I&#39;m your husband. We&#39;re going to play this game until one of us wins.&quot; His thumb traced her cheekbone. &quot;Only question is whether you know you&#39;re playing.&quot;</p><p>Her heart was trying to break out of her chest. She told it to stop.</p><p>&quot;And if I&#39;m not playing?&quot;</p><p>He smiled. It stayed on his surface.</p><p>&quot;Then you&#39;re already losing.&quot;</p><p>He kissed her.</p><p>Not the kiss she&#39;d prepared for. She&#39;d expected force — hands that grab, a mouth that takes. The monster from the file. Instead his lips were soft and patient, his tongue sliding slow against hers like he had all night. Like he had forever. He tasted like champagne and underneath it something darker, something that didn&#39;t belong at a wedding. His hand cupped her jaw, tilting her face up, and the gentleness of it made her stomach drop harder than a grip would have.</p><p>She kissed him back. That was the job.</p><p>His tongue pushed deeper and heat flooded low in her belly — a pull, a tightening, an ache she hadn&#39;t authorized. She bit his lower lip and felt him inhale sharply through his nose, the first crack in his control, and something about that small sound made her wet. Actually wet. She pressed closer, her nipples brushing his chest through the thin silk of the robe, and the friction sent a bolt of pleasure straight between her legs.</p><p>His hand slid from her jaw to the back of her neck. Threaded into her hair. Held her like she belonged there. Like she was something he&#39;d already claimed.</p><p>The possessiveness of it should have been a warning. Instead it made her clench around nothing, her body aching to be filled.</p><p>She pulled back. His grey eyes were steady. Giving nothing away.</p>",
