        {
          "id": "sc-01-06",
          "title": "Scene 6",
          "order": 5,
          "content": "<p>The Atlantic crashed outside. The roses breathed their thick, cloying scent. Her body was still humming — skin flushed, thighs shaking, the ghost of him still pulsing inside her. She could feel his wetness leaking out of her onto the sheets. She should get up. Should clean herself. Should reach for the clutch, find the earpiece, report to MERIDIAN that the mission was intact.</p><p>She didn&#39;t move.</p><p>This was the problem. This was always going to be the problem. She&#39;d gone into this with her eyes open — knew what he was, knew what she was, knew the rules. Knew that sex was just another tool in the arsenal. Bodies were weapons. She&#39;d used hers before and it had never cost her anything.</p><p>But lying here in the dark, still feeling the stretch of him inside her, still tasting champagne and smoke on her mouth — she knew, with the kind of certainty that lives in your bones, that this was different. That he was different. That she&#39;d just handed this man the one weapon she couldn&#39;t afford to lose.</p><p>And the worst part — the part that made her want to put her fist through the headboard — was that he&#39;d known it too. Had known it before she did. Before she&#39;d even walked into that gala.</p><p>*I was falling for a man who had already told me he would never fall for me.*</p><p>She rolled onto her side. Faced away from him. Stared at the wall.</p><p>&quot;Your mother&#39;s name was Catherine.&quot;</p><p>Every muscle locked.</p><p>&quot;Catherine Cross. Disappeared from your apartment in the Bronx. March 15th, 2003. You were seven. They never found her.&quot; He turned his head. &quot;You think the people who took her are connected to me.&quot;</p><p>Her mouth went dry.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;m not connected to them. I&#39;ve been hunting them since I was twenty-one — since they took my sister.&quot; A pause. &quot;I know you&#39;re FBI, Vivian. I&#39;ve known since you walked into that charity gala six months ago and looked at me like I was something you were going to put in a cell.&quot;</p><p>The room tilted. Not spinning — tilting. Like the floor had become a ramp.</p><p>She should run. Should reach for the gun. Should call MERIDIAN — except the earpiece was in her clutch and MERIDIAN was listening through a lamp fixture and she had no idea if he was hearing any of this or if she&#39;d been alone in this room for the last hour.</p><p>&quot;I married you anyway.&quot; His voice was quiet. &quot;Because I think we want the same thing.&quot;</p><p>She stared at the ceiling. Her body still humming. The window. The study. The gun in her suitcase she hadn&#39;t touched. Three exits. None of them clean.</p><p>&quot;What do you want from me?&quot;</p><p>He looked at her. And for the first time she saw something behind the grey that wasn&#39;t calculation. She didn&#39;t have a name for it. It wasn&#39;t warmth. Wasn&#39;t kindness. It was need wearing a very good disguise.</p>",
          "wordCount": 500
