          "id": "sc-03-01",
          "title": "Scene 1",
          "order": 0,
          "content": "<p>She woke to an empty bed and the smell of coffee.</p><p>Not the burnt drip coffee from her apartment in the city. This was the kind of coffee that came from machines that cost more than her first car — rich, dark, the scent threading through the penthouse like it owned the place. Which, she supposed, everything here did. Including her.</p><p>Vivian sat up. The sheets were cold on his side. He&#39;d been gone a while.</p><p>She found a note on the nightstand, written on heavy card stock in precise, controlled handwriting — the kind that looked like it had been drafted before it was committed to paper:</p><p>*Study. Come find me.*</p><p>No signature. No *good morning* or *sleep well* or any of the other things normal husbands wrote to their wives on the morning after. Just a summons.</p><p>She balled the note up. Dropped it in the wastebasket. Then she fished it out, smoothed it, and put it in her clutch. Evidence. If this ever went to trial, she&#39;d need documentation that she&#39;d been groomed, manipulated, coerced into a false marriage for the purposes of a federal investigation.</p><p>*And that&#39;s why the defense attorney would say you slept with him voluntarily. Twice.*</p><p>She got out of bed and started searching.</p><p>---</p><p>The penthouse took up the entire top floor of the east wing. She&#39;d seen the master suite last night, but daylight changed everything. Morning light showed you what darkness hid — and what it hid was how thoroughly Alexander Voss controlled his environment.</p><p>The living room was all glass and steel, furniture that looked like it had never been sat on. The bookshelves were organized by color — not author, not subject, *color* — which either meant he was a psychopath with a design budget or he didn&#39;t actually read. Both options fit.</p><p>She ran her finger along the top of the bookshelf. No dust. Staff cleaned daily.</p><p>The kitchen was pristine. White marble. Professional-grade equipment that looked unused. She opened the refrigerator — stocked with the kind of food that came from personal chefs and meal-prep services. Everything labeled. Everything dated. Even his groceries were controlled.</p><p>She moved through the rooms like she&#39;d been trained. Left to right. High to low. Every drawer, every shelf, every cabinet. Looking for what, exactly? A filing cabinet full of trafficking ledgers. A hidden room with eight hundred women chained to the walls. Something she could take to MERIDIAN and say *see, I told you he was the monster*.</p><p>She found nothing.</p><p>That was the problem. The penthouse was *too* clean. Not just physically — forensically clean. No personal documents. No photographs. No papers on the desk, no receipts in the trash, no browser history on the laptop she found in the secondary study (password-protected, naturally). It was like searching a hotel room. A very expensive, very beautiful hotel room where someone had never actually lived.</p><p>*Which meant he lived somewhere else.*</p><p>Or he kept the real evidence somewhere she hadn&#39;t found yet.</p>",
          "wordCount": 502
        },
        {
          "id": "sc-03-02",
          "title": "Scene 2",
          "order": 1,
          "content": "<p>She checked the secondary study — a smaller room off the main living area, lined with more color-coded bookshelves and a desk that looked like it had been staged. She tried the desk drawers. Locked. She could pick them. She didn&#39;t. Not yet. Picking locks left marks, and Alex noticed marks.</p><p>Everything in this place was designed to be noticed. The cameras in the corners of every room — concealed, but not concealed enough. Not to her. She counted six. All pointed at the main living areas. All recording.</p><p>He was watching. Right now, probably. Watching her search his house on a Tuesday morning in his shirt and nothing else, looking for evidence that he was a criminal mastermind.</p><p>*How did the search go?*</p><p>She looked directly into the nearest camera. Gave it a smile that didn&#39;t reach her eyes.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;m making coffee,&quot; she said to the lens. &quot;Yours is terrible, by the way.&quot;</p><p>Then she went to prove it.</p><p>---</p><p>She found him in the primary study.</p><p>She knew it was his because it was the only room in the penthouse that looked *lived in*. Papers on the desk. A laptop open, screen dark. Books that had been actually read — cracked spines, pages dog-eared, a copy of *The Art of War* with passages highlighted in yellow. A glass of whiskey on the desk, half-empty. Ice melted. From last night. He&#39;d come down here after she fell asleep.</p><p>He was standing by the window, looking out at the Atlantic. Still in the clothes from last night. Or different clothes — she couldn&#39;t tell in the morning light. His back was to her. He knew she was there. She could tell by the way his shoulders shifted. Not tension. Acknowledgment.</p><p>&quot;You searched the penthouse,&quot; he said. Not a question.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;m a curious person.&quot;</p><p>&quot;You found nothing.&quot;</p><p>&quot;I found that you organize your books by color, which says either narcissism or OCD. I found that your kitchen looks like it was photographed for a magazine and never used. I found that your secondary study is locked and your primary study is the only room in this place that looks like a human being lives in it.&quot; She leaned against the doorframe. &quot;I found that you&#39;ve been watching me search. So let&#39;s skip the part where you pretend you don&#39;t have cameras everywhere.&quot;</p><p>He turned. His grey eyes were steady. Giving nothing away.</p><p>&quot;The cameras are for security.&quot;</p><p>&quot;The cameras are for control.&quot;</p><p>&quot;They&#39;re the same thing.&quot;</p><p>She pushed off the doorframe and walked into the study. Slowly. Letting him watch her cross the room. She picked up the whiskey glass, swirled it, set it back down. Then she sat on the edge of his desk. Directly in front of him. Close enough that her knees almost touched his thighs.</p><p>&quot;I have questions,&quot; she said.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;m sure you do.&quot;</p><p>&quot;The hard drives you gave me last night. I haven&#39;t gone through them yet. But I will. And if I find anything that suggests you&#39;re lying — anything at all — I will burn you.&quot;</p>",
          "wordCount": 512
        },
        {
          "id": "sc-03-03",
          "title": "Scene 3",
          "order": 2,
          "content": "<p>&quot;I wouldn&#39;t expect anything less.&quot;</p><p>&quot;But here&#39;s what I don&#39;t understand.&quot; She tilted her head. &quot;You knew I was FBI. You married me anyway. You gave me evidence voluntarily. You *wanted* me to find it.&quot; She paused. &quot;Why?&quot;</p><p>He looked at her for a long moment. Then he reached out and took the whiskey glass from the desk. Drank the last of it. Set it down.</p><p>&quot;Because I&#39;m tired of working alone,&quot; he said. &quot;And because you&#39;re the first person I&#39;ve met who might be as obsessed with this as I am.&quot;</p><p>&quot;You don&#39;t know me.&quot;</p><p>&quot;I know you better than you think.&quot;</p><p>*Six months of cameras. Six months of watching. He knew her schedule, her habits, her tells. The hand moving toward her wrist. The way she searched rooms. The way she counted exits.*</p><p>The possessiveness of it should have been repulsive.</p><p>Instead her stomach flipped.</p><p>She hated that it flipped.</p><p>&quot;You watched me,&quot; she said. &quot;For months. Through cameras. That&#39;s not dedication. That&#39;s stalking.&quot;</p><p>&quot;It&#39;s reconnaissance.&quot;</p><p>&quot;It&#39;s illegal.&quot;</p><p>&quot;So is marrying a man you&#39;ve been sent to destroy.&quot; He tilted his head. &quot;We&#39;re both criminals, Vivian. At least I&#39;m honest about it.&quot;</p><p>She should be cataloging this. Building the case. Writing down every admission, every slip, every piece of evidence she could take to MERIDIAN and use to bring him down.</p><p>Instead she was sitting on his desk with her knees apart and his eyes on her mouth and her brain was doing something it had no business doing.</p><p>*He&#39;d probably logged this somewhere too. &#39;Wife sits on desk when she&#39;s trying to establish dominance. She thinks she&#39;s in control. She&#39;s not.&#39;*</p><p>She leaned back on her hands. Let her legs open slightly. Watched his jaw tighten.</p><p>&quot;You said I&#39;m in control,&quot; she murmured. &quot;For now.&quot;</p><p>&quot;I did.&quot;</p><p>She leaned forward. Caught the lapel of his shirt. Pulled him toward her. &quot;Then let me be in control.&quot;</p><p>He let her pull him. Let her close the distance. His hands stayed at his sides. She could feel the restraint in it — the effort it was costing him not to touch her.</p><p>She kissed him first.</p><p>Her mouth on his. Slow. Deliberate. Her tongue tracing his lower lip before she bit down. He made a sound — low, controlled — and his hands finally moved. One on her hip. One on the back of her neck.</p><p>She climbed off the desk. Pushed him back into his chair. Straddled him. Her knees on either side of his thighs. His cock was already hard beneath her and the knowledge of that — that just her kiss had done that — made her wet.</p><p>She kissed him deeper. Grinding down against him. His hands tightened on her hips and she felt the shift — the moment he stopped letting her lead.</p><p>He flipped her.</p><p>One second she was on top. The next her back was against the desk and his body was covering hers, his weight pressing her into the surface. Papers scattered. The whiskey glass fell. Didn&#39;t break.</p>",
          "wordCount": 507
